The great macroeconomic divergence
PARIS – “The global expansion has reached its peak,” warns the OECD in its latest economic outlook, and performance could suffer if downside risks materialize.
The party is not over yet: it is expected that global growth will continue in 2019 and 2020 – albeit at a slower pace.
However, economic forecasters are notoriously bad at recognizing macroeconomic turning points, and the future economic trajectory is difficult to assess.
Potential stumbling blocks abound: more aggressive monetary tightening, particularly in the United States; further escalation of protectionism; a harder-than-expected economic landing for China; and a return of tensions in the eurozone, triggered by concerns about the fate of Italian state finances.
All this, or any one of these developments, could amplify the downturn that has already set in.
A recession in the US would be frustrating for President Donald Trump, who is already looking ahead to his re-election in 2020, though such a development would not contradict known patterns.
Officially, the expansion began in June 2009, and with a duration through July 2019, it would be the longest such phase in US economic history.
Unemployment is at its lowest level since the 1960s.
Under these conditions, implementing the economic policies of the Trump administration, which consist of significant tax cuts and spending increases – essentially a stimulus package comparable to that of 2009, which was intended to avert a looming depression – would be economically nonsensical.
With that, the Federal Reserve is left with only two options: either it raises interest rates dramatically to offset the poorly timed economic stimulus measures or it capitulates.
This irresponsible game of chicken between the American fiscal and monetary authorities increases the risk of instability around the world given the global impact of the US interest rate cycle.
A global recession would come too soon for those countries whose recovery has been delayed or weak, or both.
An extreme example is Greece, where growth did not start until 2017 and unemployment still stands at nearly 20 percent.
But Greece is not alone.
In Italy, per capita GDP is no higher than in the mid-1990s.
And in Spain, France, South Korea, and other countries, unemployment remains well above pre-crisis levels.
The challenge is to re-employ long-term unemployed individuals, who face the risk of skill erosion.
To avoid lasting socio-economic damage, these countries need faster growth.
A promising international environment alone cannot solve their problems, but it would help maximize the benefits of national reforms.
The other extreme is the German labor market, which is currently in much better shape than in 2007.
In the western states, full employment prevails and economic growth is increasingly dependent on immigration: in 2017, the net inflow – not refugees but immigrants from other European countries – was around 400,000 people.
In Japan, the UK, and Poland, recovery was also characterized by the creation of many jobs.
While citizens complain about incomes, inequality, or rising housing prices, they do not complain about a lack of jobs.
Ten years ago, the crisis hit almost all developed economies simultaneously.
Today, they are neither structurally nor cyclically aligned on a single line.
This is certainly worrying, as the impending cooling of the world economy comes at a time of increasing political fragility.
Trust in governments and institutions of political decision-making is – understandably – extremely low.
Collective economic mismanagement would only further undermine this trust and fuel already rising economic nationalism.
What should be done now?
The list of tasks to be addressed begins at home. In many countries where the labor market is still out of balance, national measures are needed to strengthen economic potential and improve access to jobs.
Despite an unemployment rate of 9 percent and President Emmanuel Macron's reforms, employers in France report a skills shortage.
To change this, comprehensive measures in education are as necessary as support for mobility, incentives for job acceptance, and opening up protected sectors.
This is already happening.
In Italy, however, the ruling coalition has initiated an economic stimulus program while simultaneously proposing measures to reduce labor force participation.
This includes the withdrawal of the pension reform of 2011 as well as the introduction of a "citizen's income," which in case of inadequate planning or implementation will lead to fewer people seeking employment.
This political contradiction and less compliance with EU budget rules is the real cause for concern.
The second priority is to establish a risk equilibrium.
For some time now, there has been a political debate between hawks and doves, where the former warn that central bank purchases of assets and near-zero interest rates could foster financial instability and inflation risks. The greatest concern of the doves, however, is deflation.
Both are indeed real, although there is more reason to be concerned about deflation.
Housing bubbles can be dampened through regulatory measures, such as capping the ratio of loan amount to property value or between loan amount and income.
Regarding inflation, forecasts are regularly proven wrong.
Wages have so far slowly reacted to the declining unemployment rate.
There is a justified fear of a possible sudden increase, but after so many years of underinflation, this risk can be taken into account.
The collective costs of a temporary inflation overshoot pale in comparison to those of an early-maturing recession, which leads to lasting damage and a political backlash against economic orthodoxy.
The third priority, international coordination, is by far the most difficult to achieve, especially in the Eurozone, where the European Central Bank pursues a uniform policy for diverse economies.
The standard recipe would be for the ECB to target the average inflation rate and rely on fine-tuning the macroeconomic course through national fiscal policy.
However, given higher debts or remaining deficits, it is precisely these countries that need further growth but do not have any fiscal policy space.
Neither Greece nor Italy, let alone Spain or France, can currently consider a substantial economic stimulus program.
Without the possibility of cross-border transfers (which are also not provided for in the recent agreement between France and Germany on a mini-Eurozone budget), this is another reason why the ECB should be more bold.
This would leave the governments of countries threatened by overheating the task of cooling their economies with fiscal means, while the governments of countries still struggling for economic improvement would have to tap their economic potential.
There are many reasons to doubt that this is possible.
But it is the duty of political decision-makers to steer risks, even if the risks today are not the usual ones.
The resilience of the world economic system is at stake.
Despite favorable conditions, early cracks are appearing.
It must be prevented that these become fractures.
